STUDENTS IN THE MBL EMBRYOLOGY COURSE, SUMMER 1988

ALLENDE, Miguel
A first year graduate student in the Molecular Biology Graduate Group at U.
Penn. An undergraduate from Chile. Highly recommended by Eric Weinberg and
Robert Perry. Has not selected a thesis topic but will probably do work on
sea urchin nuclear protein genes with Weinberg.
CARNER, Kristin R. 
A first year graduate student in Vic Vaquier's lab at Scripps working with
effects of cyclic-AMP dependent kinase activity on DNA replication in early
sea urchin embryos. Primary interest is regulation of gene expression during
development. Worked previously in Robert Tjian's lab at Berkeley.
DAUGHTERY, Wayne F.
Is a Professor of Biology at San Diego State University where he teaches
Embryology and Developmental Biology. Johns Hopkins in 1966. Wishes to
get research oriented again. Well recommended by several of his faculty peers
and by Eric Davidson whom he knew previously.
DENEGRE, James
Intermediate level
project in Michael
graduate student at Wesleyan University working on a thesis
Danilchick's lab. Has a strong background in Drosophila
molecular genetics. Presently doing a thesis project on expression of a
vegetal hemisphere-specific protein in Xenopus oocytes. 
DING, Dali (male)
A graduate student at Caltech since 1986 from mainland China. Works in the
laboratory of Howard Lipshitz, an instructor in our course. Is studying
expression of the genes that specify the axis in Drosophila.
EVANS, Janice
Advanced level graduate student from University of North Carolina at Chapel
Hill studying with Brian Kay on the expression of two cytoskeletal proteins in
Xenopus oocytes. Recommended by Albert Harris.
GEYSEN, Johan
A postdoctoral student from the Zoological Institute at the Catholic
University of Leuven, Belgium; 1988. A student of Arnold De Loof.
Thesis work the moleclar cytology of insect ovaries. Author of a number of
papers in good journals. Recommended also by Spence Berry at Wesleyan.
GLIKSMAN, Neal
Second year graduate student from Ted Salmon's lab at the University of North
Carolina (Chapel Hill). Interested in microtubules and in factors regulating
the cytoskeleton. Also recommended by George Langford.
HAHN, Jill I 
A Boston University Marine Program student since 1986, interested in the
functional morphology of marine larvae. Former Harvard/Radcliffe under-
graduate; worked there with Karl Liem who wrote her an excellent letter.
Presently studying with Rudi Strickler at BU.
